Linear Submodular Maximization with Bandit Feedback

Wenjing Chen Department of Computer Science & Engineering, Texas A&M University Victoria G. Crawford Department of Computer Science & Engineering, Texas A&M University
Abstract

Submodular optimization with bandit feedback has recently been studied in a variety of contexts. In a number of real-world applications such as diversified recommender systems and data summarization, the submodular function exhibits additional linear structure. We consider developing approximation algorithms for the maximization of a submodular objective function f:2Uâ†’â„â‰¥0:ğ‘“â†’superscript2ğ‘ˆsubscriptâ„absent0f:2^{U}\to\mathbb{R}_{\geq 0}italic_f : 2 start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_U end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT â†’ blackboard_R start_POSTSUBSCRIPT â‰¥ 0 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, where f=âˆ‘i=1dwiâ¢Fiğ‘“superscriptsubscriptğ‘–1ğ‘‘subscriptğ‘¤ğ‘–subscriptğ¹ğ‘–f=\sum_{i=1}^{d}w_{i}F_{i}italic_f = âˆ‘ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i = 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_d end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_w start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT. It is assumed that we have value oracle access to the functions Fisubscriptğ¹ğ‘–F_{i}italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, but the coefficients wisubscriptğ‘¤ğ‘–w_{i}italic_w start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT are unknown, and fğ‘“fitalic_f can only be accessed via noisy queries. We develop algorithms for this setting inspired by adaptive allocation algorithms in the best-arm identification for linear bandit, with approximation guarantees arbitrarily close to the setting where we have value oracle access to fğ‘“fitalic_f. Finally, we empirically demonstrate that our algorithms make vast improvements in terms of sample efficiency compared to algorithms that do not exploit the linear structure of fğ‘“fitalic_f on instances of move recommendation.

1 Introduction

Among the most widely considered formulations is the NP-hard monotone submodular maximization problem with a cardinality constraint Nemhauser etÂ al. The setting of most existing work on SM is that we have value oracle access to fğ‘“fitalic_f, and algorithms may query any subset XâŠ‚Uğ‘‹ğ‘ˆX\subset Uitalic_X âŠ‚ italic_U and the value of fâ¢(X)ğ‘“ğ‘‹f(X)italic_f ( italic_X ) is returned.

However, in many applications it is not realistic to assume that we have value oracle access to fğ‘“fitalic_f, but rather that we can only query fğ‘“fitalic_f approximately or subject to some noise (Kempe etÂ al., 2003; Singla etÂ al., 2016; Horel and Singer, 2016; Hassidim and Singer, 2017a; Parambath etÂ al., 2018; Peng, 2021) Within this broad area of noisy access to fğ‘“fitalic_f, one important line of work consider the development of algorithms for the special case that fğ‘“fitalic_f has additional linear structure (Yue and Guestrin, 2011; Yu etÂ al., 2016; Chen etÂ al., 2017; Hiranandani etÂ al., 2020). In particular, the setting and problem is described below.

Notice that fğ‘“fitalic_f is also monotone and submodular, since it is the linear sum of monotone submodular functions. It is assumed that we have value oracle access to each of the basis functions Fisubscriptğ¹ğ‘–F_{i}italic_F start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, and we can query them on any subset SâŠ†Uğ‘†ğ‘ˆS\subseteq Uitalic_S âŠ† italic_U, but the weight vector w=(w1,w2,â€¦,wd)Twsuperscriptsubscriptğ‘¤1subscriptğ‘¤2â€¦subscriptğ‘¤ğ‘‘ğ‘‡\textbf{w}=(w_{1},w_{2},...,w_{d})^{T}w = ( italic_w start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , italic_w start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , â€¦ , italic_w start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_d end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_T end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT is unknown. We do not have oracle access to fğ‘“fitalic_f, but we may make i.i.d. R-sub-Gaussian noisy queries to fğ‘“fitalic_f where the expectation is the true value of fğ‘“fitalic_f. An important application of this setting is recommendation systems, which we will more thoroughly describe in Section 2. These assumptions on the structure of fğ‘“fitalic_f and noise fall into the well-studied linear bandit model (Soare etÂ al., 2014; Xu etÂ al., 2018), as we will explain in more detail in Section 2. The focus of existing work on SM in this setting is integrating linear bandit strategies and algorithms for SM together in order to select a subset XâŠ†Uğ‘‹ğ‘ˆX\subseteq Uitalic_X âŠ† italic_U over a series of iterations that minimizes regret (the online regret minimization setting) (Yue and Guestrin, 2011; Yu etÂ al., 2016; Chen etÂ al., 2017; Hiranandani etÂ al., 2020). Existing works emphasize the online regret minimization setting, wherein the agent strives to select a solution set with high expected function values while exploring new sets.

In the online regret minimization setting, a solution set is selected at each iteration and some corresponding noisy feedback from fğ‘“fitalic_f is returned. It is assumed that there is a penalty to choosing a bad set, e.g. a set with low fğ‘“fitalic_f value is recommended to a user, and so a balance between exploration (sampling in order to better estimate w) and exploitation (choosing sets at each iteration, e.g. to recommend to a user, that are believed to be of high value) is used in order to select sets. On the other hand, an alternative to the regret minimization setting is that of the pure exploration linear bandit (Soare etÂ al., 2014; Xu etÂ al., 2018), where as few noisy samples as possible are taken in orders to arrive at a good solution quickly. We depart from existing literature on linear submodular bandit in that we do not use the online regret minimization setting, but instead make use of ideas from pure exploration linear bandit. More specifically, our goal is to provide a solution set with a PAC-style theoretical guarantee Even-Dar etÂ al. (2002); Kalyanakrishnan etÂ al. (2012), where the bandit algorithm identifies an Ïµitalic-Ïµ\epsilonitalic_Ïµ-optimal arm with probability at least 1âˆ’Î´1ğ›¿1-\delta1 - italic_Î´, in as few samples as possible. This type of problem has been previously studied in the submodular optimization literature by Singla etÂ al. in the general case where fğ‘“fitalic_f does not have linear structure. But the linear structure of fğ‘“fitalic_f allows us to develop algorithms that make significantly fewer noisy samples (as will be demonstrated in Section 5), because we are able to learn the unknown vector w as more and more noisy samples are made.

In particular, the contributions of our paper are as follows: (i) We propose and analyze the algorithm Linear Greedy (LG), which is inspired by the standard greedy algorithm, but proceeds as Îºğœ…\kappaitalic_Îº rounds of best-arm-identification problems in the linear bandit setting. We prove that the exact function value of the output solution set of LG Sğ‘†Sitalic_S is arbitrarily close to the optimal approximation guarantee of 1âˆ’1/e11ğ‘’1-1/e1 - 1 / italic_e for cardinality constrained submodular maximization (Nemhauser etÂ al., 1978). In addition, LG chooses an optimal sample allocation strategy, and we prove a bound on the total number of noisy samples required by LG. (ii) We next propose and analyse the algorthm Linear Threshold Greedy (LinTG) which is based on the threshold greedy algorithm of Badanidiyuru and VondrÃ¡k (2014), but we propose a new linear bandit strategy in a novel setting that is distinct from best-arm-identification. LinTG is more efficient compared to LG from an algorithmic perspective, but additionally the linear bandit strategy itself is more efficient in several ways. Similar to LG, LinTG is proven to return a solution set Sğ‘†Sitalic_S that is arbitrarily close to 1âˆ’1/e11ğ‘’1-1/e1 - 1 / italic_e. (iii) Finally, we compare our algorithms to several alternative approaches to this problem on instances of movie recommendation. We find that our algorithms make significant improvements in terms of sample complexity.

1.1 Related Work

There has been a great line of work on noisy submodular maximization Horel and Singer (2016); Hassidim and Singer (2017b); Crawford etÂ al. (2019). Among these works, the most related setting assumes the noisy feedback is i.i.d Rğ‘…Ritalic_R-sub-Gaussian, which is also referred to as bandit feedback Singla etÂ al. (2016); Karimi etÂ al. (2017). The problem is also referred to as submodular bandit, which is a specific type of combinatorial multi-armed bandit problem with the reward function assumed to be submodular Chen etÂ al. (2017); Takemori etÂ al. (2020); Hiranandani etÂ al. (2020). The main focus of these works are regret minimization. Among the works studying submodular bandit, the linear submodular bandit is a specific problem with the same objective function as us Yue and Guestrin (2011); Takemori etÂ al. (2020); Yu etÂ al. (2016), i.e., the objective function fğ‘“fitalic_f can be expressed by the linear sum of known submodular functions with unknown weights. The problem was first introduced by Yue and Guestrin (2011), who studied the problem with the goal of regret minimization. Under this setting, the strategy is to explore new choices of the subsets while also exploiting previous samples to select good ones. Therefore, the algorithm should be encouraged to choose the sets with higher function values while the main focus of our paper is to study the linear submodular bandit under best-arm identification setting, where the objective is to find the best solution set in fewer queries. One obvious approach to this problem is to simply take sufficiently many noisy samples so that fğ‘“fitalic_f is approximated very closely for all sets that are to be queried, and then apply existing algorithms for SM on the approximation of fğ‘“fitalic_f. The downsides of such an approach is that not only is it unnecessary to approximate fğ‘“fitalic_f so closely when making decisions during an algorithm, but this approach does not exploit the linear structure of fğ‘“fitalic_f. A difficulty with such algorithms is that the large number of noisy samples can make such an approach impractical.

Another related line of work is the problem of identifying the best element in linear bandit (The arms are single elements in the universe.), which is first studied in Soare etÂ al. (2014). The authors proposed static allocation strategies and adaptive strategies based on successive elimination. Later on, there are a large line of works that proposed more adaptive algorithms Xu etÂ al. (2018); Degenne etÂ al. (2020). Xu etÂ al. (2018) proposed an algorithm named LinGap which is claimed to be fully adaptive and performed better than those in Soare etÂ al. (2014). Degenne etÂ al. (2020) proposed the first algorithm that is asymptotically optimal.

Linear submodular functions arise in a wide range of applications including recommender systems, weighted coverage, and facility location. Next, we describe the application of the recommender system as an example to illustrate our problem setting.

2.1 Motivating application: diversified recommender systems

Herein, the submodular function is the expected total clicks from recommending the list of items. 2.3 Concentration Properties of Estimation of Weight Vector

Our estimate of w is used alongside a concentration inequality that tells us how accurate our estimate is in the form of a confidence interval. In contrast to concentration inequalities such as Hoeffdingâ€™s which is for a real-valued random variable, the confidence region in the concentration inequality we use can be geometrically interpreted as a ellipsoid. Pulling different arms results in the shrinking of the confidence region along different directions. The following is the concentration inequality that we will use for our least-squares estimator. The result is obtained from Thm. 2 in Abbasi-Yadkori etÂ al. (2011). The proof can be found in the appendix.

Proposition 1.

3 The Standard Greedy Algorithm

(2018) to select the element to add to the solution set. We provide the algorithm description and overview as follows.

This concludes the description of our algorithm LG.

Technical challenges. We now discuss the technical difficulties of developing LG. It should be noted that the portion of LG where we are repeatedly making noisy queries in order to determine the element of approximately highest marginal gain with high probability could be replaced by any existing algorithm for Ïµitalic-Ïµ\epsilonitalic_Ïµ-approximate best-arm-identification in linear bandit where the arms correspond to the marginal gains of adding each of the nğ‘›nitalic_n elements of Uğ‘ˆUitalic_U to the current solution Sğ‘†Sitalic_S. In this case, each round of LG would be a new instance of linear bandit. In particular, we develop an algorithm using the static allocation strategy as the subroutine in Section A.1. However, such algorithms overlook that the weight vector estimated in different rounds of the algorithm are the same and donâ€™t reuse samples gained from the past rounds while our algorithm LG is different because we do not view each round of LG as a new instance of linear bandit, but instead we use information gained about w from past rounds of the greedy algorithm. In addition, LG may sample marginal gains corresponding to arms of the previous rounds of the greedy algorithm. Thus, our contribution extends beyond merely integrating best-arm identification into the greedy algorithm. We also develop an algorithm, inspired by Xu etÂ al. (2018), which efficiently reuses samples from previous rounds, thereby enhancing the algorithmâ€™s performance and efficiency.

Theoretical Guarantees. Finally, we present the theoretical guarantees of LG. 4 Threshold Greedy with Adaptive Allocation strategy

In the last section, we present our algorithm LG which is based on the standard greedy algorithm but with linear bandit feedback. However, the implementation of LG poses several challenges in terms of its scalability: (i) Finding the allocation strategy in LG necessitates solving Oâ¢(Îºâ¢n2)ğ‘‚ğœ…superscriptğ‘›2O(\kappa n^{2})italic_O ( italic_Îº italic_n start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ) linear programming problems, (ii) LG requires updating the inverse of matrix A and confidence interval every time an arm is pulled, (iii) LG is sensitive to the gap between the marginal gains of different elements and therefore may need many samples in the case that there exist elements that have an expected reward close to optimal, (iv) the standard greedy algorithm is less efficient compared to alternative greedy algorithms even in the exact value oracle setting. Motivated by these weaknesses of LG, we introduce an alternative algorithm Linear Threshold Greedy (LinTG) which is based on the threshold greedy algorithm of Badanidiyuru and VondrÃ¡k (2014), but incorporates a linear bandit strategy.

We now describe LinTG, pseudocode for which is given in Algorithm 2. LinTG proceeds in a series of rounds (Lines 12 to 35), each round corresponding to a threshold value wğ‘¤witalic_w. wğ‘¤witalic_w is initialized to be an approximation of the maximum fğ‘“fitalic_f value of a singleton in Uğ‘ˆUitalic_U. During each round of LinTG, we iterate over the ground set Uğ‘ˆUitalic_U and make a decision about whether to add each element aâˆˆUğ‘ğ‘ˆa\in Uitalic_a âˆˆ italic_U to our solution Sğ‘†Sitalic_S or not depending on whether the marginal gain Î”â¢fâ¢(S,a)Î”ğ‘“ğ‘†ğ‘\Delta f(S,a)roman_Î” italic_f ( italic_S , italic_a ) is above wğ‘¤witalic_w. LinTG decides whether to add each aâˆˆUğ‘ğ‘ˆa\in Uitalic_a âˆˆ italic_U to Sğ‘†Sitalic_S or not on Lines 14 to 33 based on a sampling procedure in a linear bandit-like setting, and is analogous to the best-arm-identification procedure in LG. Throughout the algorithm, we keep track of the following parameters: the covariance matrix A, vector b, and the set of marginal gain vectors to sample from, which is denoted as ğ’³ğ’³\mathcal{X}caligraphic_X. Here we denote the size of ğ’³ğ’³\mathcal{X}caligraphic_X as mğ‘šmitalic_m. In this algorithm, ğ’³ğ’³\mathcal{X}caligraphic_X includes all the past marginal gains that have been evaluated. 5 Experiments

In this section, we conduct experiments on the instance of movie recommendation. The dataset used in the experiments are subsets extracted from the MovieLens 25M dataset Harper and Konstan (2015), which comprises 162,541162541162,541162 , 541 ratings for 13,8161381613,81613 , 816 movies, each associated with 1,12811281,1281 , 128 topics. We compare the sample complexity of different algorithms with different values of size constraint Îºğœ…\kappaitalic_Îº, error parameter Ïµitalic-Ïµ\epsilonitalic_Ïµ, and different datasets with different values of dğ‘‘ditalic_d. When Îºğœ…\kappaitalic_Îº is varied, Ïµitalic-Ïµ\epsilonitalic_Ïµ is fixed at 0.10.10.10.1. The dataset movie60 contains 60606060 elements with d=5ğ‘‘5d=5italic_d = 5, |V|=500ğ‘‰500|V|=500| italic_V | = 500. The dataset movie5000 contains n=5000ğ‘›5000n=5000italic_n = 5000 elements with d=30ğ‘‘30d=30italic_d = 30, |V|=1000ğ‘‰1000|V|=1000| italic_V | = 1000. For the algorithms comparing different values of dğ‘‘ditalic_d, we run the algorithms on different datasets with different values of dğ‘‘ditalic_d. Here nğ‘›nitalic_n and |V|ğ‘‰|V|| italic_V | are fixed at 500500500500. Additional details about the applications, setup, and results can be found in Section C in the supplementary material.

We present the results in terms of the number of evaluations in Figure 1. Due to the high sample complexity and heavy computational burden resulting from solving the linear programming problem, here we only run the algorithms EXP-GREEDY, LinGREEDY, and LinTG on the relatively small dataset movie60. From the results on the dataset movie60, we can see that the sample complexity of the algorithms that donâ€™t consider the linear structure (EXP-GREEDY and TG) is much higher than the algorithms proposed in this paper, which demonstrates the advantages of our proposed methods. In particular, the algorithms LinTG and LinTG-H have the lowest sample complexity compared with other methods. Besides, we notice that the algorithm when Ïµitalic-Ïµ\epsilonitalic_Ïµ is very small, the algorithms TG has an increase on the sample complexity. From Figure 1(d), we can see the sample complexity of the algorithm LinTG-H increases as dğ‘‘ditalic_d increases, which is consistent with our theoretical results on sample complexity.

A.1 Warm-up: static allocation strategy

[2014]. The theoretical guarantee is stated below. In particular, we first give a description of the static strategy. Next, we provide the detailed statement and proofs of Theorem 4.

The algorithm proceeds in rounds. Although this allocation ratio is not asymptotically optimal and follows a similar principle to the CLUCB algorithm, there are notable differences: (i) Our algorithm LG leverages the linear structure, and the concentration inequality used is derived from the linear bandit literature. (ii). The linear submodular bandit algorithm allows us to exploit sampling results from past greedy rounds while in the CLUCB algorithm developed for the general bandit setting, we are not allowed to do that. In our experiments, we also adopt this allocation ratio.

A.2.2 Proof of Theorem 2

Appendix B Appendix for Section 4

In this section, we present the proofs of theoretical results from Section 4. First, in Section B.1, we present and prove the Lemma 6 concerning the theoretical guarantee on the value of the evaluated marginal gain and sample complexity of LinTG. Next, we apply the theoretical results of Lemma 6 and prove the final theoretical guarantee for the linear threshold greedy algorithm LinTG in Algorithm 2.

Appendix C Appendix for Section 5

In this section, we present supplementary material to Section 5. In particular, we present the missing details about the experimental setup in Section C.1, and the additional experimental results in Section C.2.

C.1 Experimental setup

First of all, we provide more details about the movie recommendation dataset MovieLens 25M dataset Harper and Konstan [2015] used to evaluate the algorithms proposed in the main paper. The dataset contains ratings on a 5-star scale of X=13,816ğ‘‹13816X=13,816italic_X = 13 , 816 movies by the users. Each movie xğ‘¥xitalic_x is associated with 1,12811281,1281 , 128 topics and a relevance score is assigned to each movie and each topic. Here we use Gâ¢(x,i)ğºğ‘¥ğ‘–G(x,i)italic_G ( italic_x , italic_i ) to denote the relevance score of movie xğ‘¥xitalic_x and the topic iğ‘–iitalic_i. In addition, we use Râ¢(a,x)ğ‘…ğ‘ğ‘¥R(a,x)italic_R ( italic_a , italic_x ) to denote the rating of user ağ‘aitalic_a for the movie xğ‘¥xitalic_x. Since the number of topics is too large for our experiments, we select a small subset of topics by the following procedure. To extract the most relevant topics, we conduct correlation analysis to select a subset of topics. For each pair of features iğ‘–iitalic_i and jğ‘—jitalic_j, if Câ¢oâ¢râ¢(i,j)â‰¥0.4ğ¶ğ‘œğ‘Ÿğ‘–ğ‘—0.4Cor(i,j)\geq 0.4italic_C italic_o italic_r ( italic_i , italic_j ) â‰¥ 0.4 then either iğ‘–iitalic_i or jğ‘—jitalic_j is removed from the tag list. Subsequently, we remove any features that are negatively or weakly correlated to the ratings, i.e., âˆ€ifor-allğ‘–\forall iâˆ€ italic_i if Câ¢oâ¢râ¢(i,s)â‰¤0.2ğ¶ğ‘œğ‘Ÿğ‘–ğ‘ 0.2Cor(i,s)\leq 0.2italic_C italic_o italic_r ( italic_i , italic_s ) â‰¤ 0.2 then iğ‘–iitalic_i is removed from the list. In this way, we select 79797979 tags. Then we randomly select different number of topics to use as the features.

Next, we describe more details about the algorithms that we compare to in the experiments. The TG algorithm that we compare to is based on the threshold greedy algorithm with the evaluation of marginal gain being replaced by the repeated sampling approach. Therefore, by applying the Hoeffdingâ€™s inequality, TG achieves the same approximation ratio as our algorithms. The algorithm EXP-GREEDY is proposed in Singla etÂ al. [2016] and is based on the standard greedy algorithm with the element selecting procedure in each greedy round replaced by the CLUCB algorithm for best arm identification for general bandit. The algorithm TG doesnâ€™t utilize the linear structure either. As a result, these algorithms canâ€™t be used to reuse previous samples.

C.2 Exprimental results

The additional results of the experiments are presented in Figure 2. From the results, we can see that the exact function value of different algorithms are almost the same. On the â€movie5000â€ dataset, the sample complexity of our proposed method LinTG-H is much smaller than TG, which demonstrates the sample efficiency of our algorithm.
